1
00:00:08,091 --> 00:00:09,259
[exhales]

2
00:00:14,973 --> 00:00:16,182
[sighs]

3
00:00:16,266 --> 00:00:17,434
[door clicks open]

4
00:00:19,310 --> 00:00:21,312
Eleanor? Come on in.

5
00:00:23,106 --> 00:00:24,941
Hi, Eleanor. I'm Michael.

6
00:00:26,067 --> 00:00:27,152
How are you today?

7
00:00:27,360 --> 00:00:29,112
I'm great. Thanks for asking.

8
00:00:30,030 --> 00:00:32,699
Oh, one question. Where am I?

9
00:00:32,782 --> 00:00:34,451
Who are you, and what's going on?

10
00:00:35,410 --> 00:00:39,414
Right, so, you,
Eleanor Shellstrop, are dead.

11
00:00:39,789 --> 00:00:41,458
Your life on Earth has ended,

12
00:00:41,541 --> 00:00:45,170
and you are now in the next phase
of your existence in the universe.

13
00:00:47,964 --> 00:00:51,718
Cool. Cool. I have some questions.

14
00:00:51,968 --> 00:00:53,052
Thought you might. [chuckles]

15
00:00:53,219 --> 00:00:55,722
How did I die? I don't remember.

16
00:00:55,847 --> 00:00:58,933
Yes, um, in cases of traumatic
or embarrassing deaths,

17
00:00:59,017 --> 00:01:03,480
we erase the memory to allow
for a peaceful transition.

18
00:01:03,938 --> 00:01:05,648
Are you sure you want to hear?

19
00:01:06,024 --> 00:01:09,360
All right, so you were
in a grocery store parking lot.

20
00:01:09,444 --> 00:01:14,115
You dropped a bottle of something called,
"Lonely Gal Margarita Mix for One."

21
00:01:14,407 --> 00:01:18,369
And when you bent down to pick it up,
a long column of shopping carts

22
00:01:19,245 --> 00:01:21,498
that were being returned to
the shopping cart collection area

23
00:01:21,956 --> 00:01:25,043
rolled out of control
and plowed right into you.

24
00:01:25,418 --> 00:01:28,755
-Oof. That's how I died?
-No, sorry, there's more.

25
00:01:29,214 --> 00:01:32,175
You were able to grab on to the front
of the column of shopping carts,

26
00:01:32,258 --> 00:01:34,302
but it'd swept you right out
into the street

27
00:01:34,385 --> 00:01:36,095
where you were struck and killed

28
00:01:36,179 --> 00:01:39,390
by a mobile billboard truck advertising

29
00:01:40,099 --> 00:01:43,186
an erectile dysfunction pill
called "Engorge-ulate."

30
00:01:44,229 --> 00:01:47,357
Funnily enough, the first EMT to arrive
was an ex-boyfriend of yours--

31
00:01:47,524 --> 00:01:48,942
Okay, that's... I get it, thank you.

32
00:01:49,109 --> 00:01:52,153
-Oh, okay, sorry.
-Um, so who was right?

33
00:01:53,029 --> 00:01:55,031
I mean about all of this?

34
00:01:55,448 --> 00:01:58,118
Well, let's see.
Hindus are a little bit right,

35
00:01:58,201 --> 00:02:02,080
Muslims a little bit.
Jews, Christians, Buddhists,

36
00:02:02,539 --> 00:02:05,416
every religion guessed about 5%,

37
00:02:05,875 --> 00:02:08,545
-except for Doug Forcett.
-Who's Doug Forcett?

38
00:02:09,129 --> 00:02:13,466
Well, Doug was a stoner kid
who lived in Calgary during the 1970s.

39
00:02:13,883 --> 00:02:15,885
One night,
he got really high on mushrooms,

40
00:02:15,969 --> 00:02:18,138
and his best friend, Randy, said,

41
00:02:18,513 --> 00:02:20,890
"Hey, what do you think
happens after we die?"

42
00:02:21,182 --> 00:02:24,602
And Doug just launched
into this long monologue

43
00:02:24,686 --> 00:02:27,230
where he got like 92% correct.

44
00:02:27,313 --> 00:02:29,983
[chuckles] I mean, we couldn't believe
what we were hearing.

45
00:02:30,066 --> 00:02:31,484
That's him, actually, right up there.

46
00:02:31,568 --> 00:02:33,278
{\an8}He's pretty famous around here.

47
00:02:33,945 --> 00:02:35,280
I'm very lucky to have that.

48
00:02:35,363 --> 00:02:36,531
-So...
-[chuckles]

49
00:02:36,614 --> 00:02:38,533
Maybe my biggest question. Am I...

50
00:02:39,159 --> 00:02:40,535
I mean, is this...

51
00:02:42,912 --> 00:02:43,997
Or...

52
00:02:45,123 --> 00:02:50,086
Well, it's not the heaven-or-hell
idea that you were raised on.

53
00:02:50,795 --> 00:02:53,882
But generally speaking, in the afterlife,

54
00:02:53,965 --> 00:02:57,051
there's a Good Place
and there's a Bad Place.

55
00:02:58,761 --> 00:03:00,138
You're in The Good Place.

56
00:03:00,722 --> 00:03:02,765
-[exhales sharply]
-You're okay, Eleanor.

57
00:03:02,891 --> 00:03:04,392
You're in The Good Place.

58
00:03:04,559 --> 00:03:05,894
Well, that's good.

59
00:03:06,102 --> 00:03:07,854
Sure is. [laughs]

60
00:03:07,979 --> 00:03:10,023
Okay, let's take a walk, shall we?

61
00:03:12,358 --> 00:03:16,613
Oh, did I have a purse?
No, I'm dead, right. Okay.

62
00:03:21,743 --> 00:03:23,119
So, this is how it works.

63
00:03:23,202 --> 00:03:26,414
{\an8}The Good Place is divided
into distinct neighborhoods.

64
00:03:26,664 --> 00:03:30,293
Each one contains exactly 322 people

65
00:03:30,376 --> 00:03:32,170
{\an8}who have been perfectly selected

66
00:03:32,253 --> 00:03:36,007
{\an8}to blend together into
a blissful harmonic balance.

67
00:03:36,341 --> 00:03:38,343
{\an8}Do all the neighborhoods look like this?

68
00:03:38,426 --> 00:03:42,180
{\an8}No, every neighborhood is unique.
Some have warm weather, some cold.

69
00:03:42,263 --> 00:03:44,182
{\an8}Some are cities, some farmland.

70
00:03:44,265 --> 00:03:47,143
{\an8}But in each one, every blade of grass,

71
00:03:47,227 --> 00:03:50,396
{\an8}every ladybug, every detail has been

72
00:03:50,480 --> 00:03:53,900
{\an8}precisely designed and calibrated
for its residents.

73
00:03:53,983 --> 00:03:56,402
{\an8}There's a lot of frozen yogurt places.

74
00:03:56,486 --> 00:03:57,862
{\an8}Yeah. [sighs]

75
00:03:57,946 --> 00:03:59,781
{\an8}That's the one thing we put
in all the neighborhoods.

76
00:03:59,864 --> 00:04:03,284
People love frozen yogurt.
I don't know what to tell you.

77
00:04:04,202 --> 00:04:06,287
{\an8}You're gonna have a million
more questions, I know.

78
00:04:06,371 --> 00:04:08,957
{\an8}For right now, better grab a seat.

79
00:04:09,040 --> 00:04:10,667
{\an8}Movie's about to begin.

80
00:04:11,918 --> 00:04:13,628
{\an8}[indistinct chatter]

81
00:04:16,256 --> 00:04:18,883
{\an8}<i>Ah.</i> [chuckles]<i> Hello, everyone.</i>

82
00:04:18,967 --> 00:04:23,304
{\an8}<i>And welcome to your first day</i>
<i>in the afterlife.</i>

83
00:04:23,805 --> 00:04:26,808
<i>You were all, simply put, good people.</i>

84
00:04:27,225 --> 00:04:29,477
<i>But how do we know that you were good?</i>

85
00:04:29,560 --> 00:04:31,020
<i>How are we sure?</i>

86
00:04:31,813 --> 00:04:35,149
<i>During your time on Earth,</i>
<i>every one of your actions</i>

87
00:04:35,233 --> 00:04:38,194
<i>had a positive or a negative value,</i>

88
00:04:38,319 --> 00:04:43,032
<i>depending on how much good or bad</i>
<i>that action put into the universe.</i>

89
00:04:43,408 --> 00:04:47,537
<i>Every sandwich you ate,</i>
<i>every time you bought a magazine,</i>

90
00:04:47,620 --> 00:04:49,872
<i>every single thing you did</i>

91
00:04:49,956 --> 00:04:52,875
<i>had an effect that rippled out over time</i>

92
00:04:52,959 --> 00:04:56,546
<i>and ultimately created</i>
<i>some amount of good or bad.</i>

93
00:04:56,629 --> 00:04:58,673
<i>You know how some people</i>
<i>pull into the breakdown lane</i>

94
00:04:58,756 --> 00:04:59,757
<i>when there's traffic?</i>

95
00:04:59,841 --> 00:05:03,136
<i>And they think to themselves,</i>
<i>"Ah, who cares? No one's watching."</i>

96
00:05:04,053 --> 00:05:05,430
<i>We were watching.</i>

97
00:05:05,513 --> 00:05:06,556
<i>Surprise!</i>

98
00:05:06,681 --> 00:05:08,016
[audience laughing]

99
00:05:08,182 --> 00:05:10,768
<i>Anyway, when your time on Earth has ended,</i>

100
00:05:10,852 --> 00:05:13,604
<i>we calculate the total value of your life</i>

101
00:05:13,688 --> 00:05:16,774
<i>using our perfectly accurate</i>
<i>measuring system.</i>

102
00:05:16,858 --> 00:05:19,819
<i>Only the people</i>
<i>with the very highest scores,</i>

103
00:05:19,902 --> 00:05:21,279
<i>the true cream of the crop,</i>

104
00:05:21,362 --> 00:05:23,239
<i>get to come here, to The Good Place.</i>

105
00:05:23,614 --> 00:05:25,575
<i>What happens to everyone else, you ask?</i>

106
00:05:26,159 --> 00:05:27,535
<i>Don't worry about it.</i>

107
00:05:27,952 --> 00:05:32,040
<i>The point is, you are here because you </i>
<i>lived one of the very best lives</i>

108
00:05:32,123 --> 00:05:33,207
<i>that could be lived.</i>

109
00:05:33,291 --> 00:05:38,254
<i>And you won't be alone.</i>
<i>Your true soulmate is here too.</i>

110
00:05:38,379 --> 00:05:39,964
-[crowd gasps and murmurs]
<i>-That's right.</i>

111
00:05:40,048 --> 00:05:41,049
<i>Soulmates are real.</i>

112
00:05:41,132 --> 00:05:44,093
<i>One of the other people </i>
<i>in your neighborhood</i>

113
00:05:44,177 --> 00:05:48,514
<i>is your actual soulmate,</i>
<i>and you will spend eternity together.</i>

114
00:05:49,932 --> 00:05:52,351
<i>So welcome to eternal happiness.</i>

115
00:05:52,435 --> 00:05:54,437
<i>Welcome to The Good Place.</i>

116
00:05:54,687 --> 00:05:55,980
<i>Sponsored by...</i>

117
00:05:56,064 --> 00:05:58,066
<i>Otters holding hands while they sleep.</i>

118
00:05:58,191 --> 00:05:59,650
<i>You know the way you feel when you see</i>

119
00:05:59,734 --> 00:06:02,153
<i>a picture of two otters holding hands?</i>

120
00:06:02,528 --> 00:06:05,448
<i>That's how you're gonna feel every day.</i>

121
00:06:05,531 --> 00:06:06,991
[audience applauding]

122
00:06:08,826 --> 00:06:11,412
So who is in The Bad Place
that would shock me?

123
00:06:11,496 --> 00:06:15,583
Uh... Well, Mozart, Picasso, Elvis,

124
00:06:15,666 --> 00:06:17,627
basically every artist ever,

125
00:06:17,710 --> 00:06:20,213
uh, every US president except Lincoln.

126
00:06:20,296 --> 00:06:23,007
[Eleanor] That sounds about right.
What about Florence Nightingale?

127
00:06:23,091 --> 00:06:25,093
[Michael] It was close,
but, no, she didn't make it.

128
00:06:25,176 --> 00:06:29,847
Wow, all those amazing people down there,
it just seems so hard to believe.

129
00:06:29,931 --> 00:06:33,226
Again, it's an incredibly
selective system.

130
00:06:33,309 --> 00:06:34,936
Most people don't make it here.

131
00:06:35,561 --> 00:06:39,690
But you, a lawyer who got
innocent people off death row,

132
00:06:39,774 --> 00:06:41,692
you're special, Eleanor.

133
00:06:42,527 --> 00:06:46,030
And by the way, welcome to your new home.

134
00:06:46,864 --> 00:06:48,783
-[Michael] Oh, it's perfect, isn't it?
-[gasps]

135
00:06:48,866 --> 00:06:50,284
You see, in The Good Place,

136
00:06:50,368 --> 00:06:55,248
every person gets to live in a home that
perfectly matches his or her true essence.

137
00:06:56,082 --> 00:06:57,333
Cool.

138
00:06:57,416 --> 00:07:00,211
So I guess that's why
my house, for example,

139
00:07:00,294 --> 00:07:02,296
is this adorable little cottage,

140
00:07:02,380 --> 00:07:05,258
whereas other people might
have homes that are bigger,

141
00:07:05,758 --> 00:07:07,176
like that one.

142
00:07:07,718 --> 00:07:10,471
[Michael] Exactly.
Oh, I'm so happy you get it.

143
00:07:11,097 --> 00:07:15,435
As you can see, the interior has been
decorated just as you like it,

144
00:07:15,518 --> 00:07:17,770
in the Icelandic primitive style.

145
00:07:18,604 --> 00:07:22,525
Oh, oh, and, uh, of course,
you love clowns, so...

146
00:07:24,360 --> 00:07:25,736
I do love clowns.

147
00:07:25,903 --> 00:07:28,990
Now, let me show you the, uh,
the video system here.

148
00:07:29,782 --> 00:07:31,367
[shimmering tone]

149
00:07:31,951 --> 00:07:34,245
You can review everything
that happened in your life

150
00:07:34,328 --> 00:07:35,580
from your point of view.

151
00:07:36,622 --> 00:07:37,915
There we go.

152
00:07:37,999 --> 00:07:40,585
This is your human rights
mission to Ukraine.

153
00:07:41,335 --> 00:07:42,920
I mean, you got
a ton of points for that one.

154
00:07:43,004 --> 00:07:44,714
It really put you over the top.

155
00:07:45,673 --> 00:07:46,966
Oh.

156
00:07:47,049 --> 00:07:48,676
Chidi, come on in.

157
00:07:49,886 --> 00:07:53,431
Eleanor? I'm Chidi Anagonye,

158
00:07:53,848 --> 00:07:56,142
and you are my soulmate.

159
00:07:58,227 --> 00:08:00,646
Cool! Bring it in, man.

160
00:08:00,897 --> 00:08:03,649
Now, excuse me.
I have other people to attend to.

161
00:08:04,567 --> 00:08:05,943
So where you from, Chidi?

162
00:08:06,194 --> 00:08:09,530
Well, I was born in Nigeria,
raised in Senegal,

163
00:08:09,614 --> 00:08:11,741
but my work took me all over the place.

164
00:08:11,824 --> 00:08:14,035
Australia, Hong Kong, Paris.

165
00:08:14,869 --> 00:08:16,120
What about you?

166
00:08:16,204 --> 00:08:18,664
Uh, well, I... I was born in Phoenix.

167
00:08:18,748 --> 00:08:20,041
-Mmm-hmm.
-Arizona.

168
00:08:20,166 --> 00:08:22,877
And then I went to school
in Tempe, Arizona.

169
00:08:23,085 --> 00:08:26,380
And then I moved back to Phoenix, Arizona.

170
00:08:28,549 --> 00:08:29,842
Your English is amazing.

171
00:08:30,301 --> 00:08:32,845
Oh! I'm actually speaking French.

172
00:08:32,929 --> 00:08:35,556
This place just translates
whatever you say

173
00:08:35,640 --> 00:08:38,142
into a language the other person
can understand.

174
00:08:38,226 --> 00:08:40,019
-So it's incredible.
-Whoa.

175
00:08:40,102 --> 00:08:42,855
-And now I want to say this.
-Mmm-kay.

176
00:08:43,314 --> 00:08:44,440
Eleanor.

177
00:08:44,732 --> 00:08:49,904
I have spent my entire life in pursuit
of fundamental truths about the universe.

178
00:08:50,071 --> 00:08:54,992
And now we can actually learn about them
together as soulmates.

179
00:08:56,244 --> 00:08:57,787
It's overwhelming.

180
00:08:59,413 --> 00:09:03,000
Chidi. You'll stand by my side
no matter what, right?

181
00:09:03,251 --> 00:09:07,338
-Of course I will.
-Promise me. Say, "I promise

182
00:09:07,421 --> 00:09:10,591
I will never betray you for any reason."

183
00:09:10,675 --> 00:09:11,801
Eleanor, I swear

184
00:09:11,884 --> 00:09:15,763
that I will never say or do anything

185
00:09:15,846 --> 00:09:17,765
to cause you any harm.

186
00:09:17,848 --> 00:09:18,933
Good.

187
00:09:19,267 --> 00:09:20,810
Because those aren't my memories.

188
00:09:20,893 --> 00:09:22,937
I wasn't a lawyer.
I never went to the Ukraine.

189
00:09:23,020 --> 00:09:25,189
I hate clowns.

190
00:09:25,398 --> 00:09:27,108
There's been a big mistake.

191
00:09:28,276 --> 00:09:30,361
I'm not supposed to be here.

192
00:09:34,156 --> 00:09:35,324
Wait, what?

193
00:09:44,875 --> 00:09:46,335
Are you sure this isn't you?

194
00:09:46,419 --> 00:09:50,172
Yeah, man, I'm pretty sure
I wasn't a death-row lawyer

195
00:09:50,256 --> 00:09:53,467
who collected clown paintings
and rescued orphans.

196
00:09:53,551 --> 00:09:55,720
They got my name right, but nothing else.

197
00:09:55,803 --> 00:09:58,431
I mean, somebody royally
forked up. [chuckles]

198
00:09:59,432 --> 00:10:00,933
Somebody forked up.

199
00:10:01,434 --> 00:10:02,935
Why can't I say "fork"?

200
00:10:03,019 --> 00:10:04,729
If you're trying to curse, you can't here.

201
00:10:04,812 --> 00:10:06,564
I guess a lot of people
in this neighborhood

202
00:10:06,647 --> 00:10:08,190
don't like it, so it's prohibited.

203
00:10:08,274 --> 00:10:09,275
That's bull-shirt.

204
00:10:09,358 --> 00:10:13,029
So, if you're not this person,
then who are you?

205
00:10:13,112 --> 00:10:14,363
What did you do for a living?

206
00:10:14,447 --> 00:10:17,158
I was... In...

207
00:10:17,241 --> 00:10:18,284
Sales.

208
00:10:18,451 --> 00:10:21,495
So we sell two products here,
NasaPRO and NasaPRO Silver.

209
00:10:21,579 --> 00:10:22,705
We aim this at seniors.

210
00:10:22,913 --> 00:10:24,999
Now, you can't legally call it "medicine"

211
00:10:25,207 --> 00:10:28,169
because it doesn't technically work

212
00:10:28,252 --> 00:10:32,298
and it is technically chalk,
so what you're gonna want to do--

213
00:10:32,381 --> 00:10:35,343
You need me to lie to old people
and scare them into buying fake medicine.

214
00:10:35,426 --> 00:10:37,345
I get it, man. Which one's my desk?

215
00:10:38,346 --> 00:10:42,683
So your job was to defraud the elderly...

216
00:10:42,767 --> 00:10:45,144
Sorry, the sick and elderly?

217
00:10:45,227 --> 00:10:46,395
But I was very good at it.

218
00:10:46,479 --> 00:10:48,814
I was the top salesperson
five years running.

219
00:10:48,898 --> 00:10:49,982
Okay, but that's worse.

220
00:10:50,274 --> 00:10:52,526
I mean, you, you do get how that's worse,

221
00:10:52,610 --> 00:10:54,070
right?

222
00:10:55,488 --> 00:10:58,491
You know, maybe it's a test.

223
00:10:58,574 --> 00:11:01,160
Maybe if you go to Michael
and you tell him the truth,

224
00:11:01,369 --> 00:11:02,828
you'll pass the test

225
00:11:02,912 --> 00:11:04,413
-and you'll get to stay.
-No way.

226
00:11:04,497 --> 00:11:06,040
I can't risk going to The Bad Place.

227
00:11:06,248 --> 00:11:09,335
Okay, well, maybe it's not actually, like,
all that bad.

228
00:11:09,543 --> 00:11:11,212
Let's just get some information first.

229
00:11:11,420 --> 00:11:12,880
We'll ask Janet. Hey, Janet?

230
00:11:12,963 --> 00:11:14,173
-Hi there.
-[exclaims]

231
00:11:14,256 --> 00:11:15,174
How can I help you?

232
00:11:15,257 --> 00:11:16,675
What the fork? Who are you?

233
00:11:16,759 --> 00:11:18,135
I'm Janet.

234
00:11:18,219 --> 00:11:20,471
I'm the informational assistant
here in The Good Place.

235
00:11:20,554 --> 00:11:22,848
She's like this walking database.

236
00:11:22,932 --> 00:11:26,894
You can ask her about
the creation of the universe, or history--

237
00:11:26,977 --> 00:11:31,065
Oh, there was a guy who lived
in Avondale, Arizona, around 2002.

238
00:11:31,148 --> 00:11:32,983
His name was Kevin Paltonic.

239
00:11:33,067 --> 00:11:34,527
-Is he gay?
-No.

